    "content": "The food color industry is rapidly shifting from synthetic petroleum-based dyes to natural alternatives, driven by consumer clean-label demand and regulatory pressure. FDA initiatives under MAHA aim to eliminate six synthetic dyes (Green No. 3, Red No. 40, Yellow No. 5/6, Blue No. 1/2) by end-2027, with companies pledging removals by 2026-2028; many food firms like Kellogg's, General Mills, Nestle committed via FDA tracker. FDA broadened \"no artificial colors\" claims for petroleum-free products (even synthetic non-petroleum) and approved expansions like spirulina but paused beetroot red/spirulina effective dates indefinitely due to GMO/safety objections from groups like GMO/Toxin Free USA. Key companies: Sensient (expanding US natural production with $250M investment), Givaudan, Oterra, dsm-firmenich, DDW, ADM, ROHA, GNT USA, Phytolon. Trends: Natural colorants market growing from $1.65-4.98B in 2025 to $3-5B+ by 2032 (CAGR 6-9%), led by carotenoids/plant sources in beverages/confectionery; clean/organic/plant-based focus. Innovations: Biofermentation (e.g., Kerry's Truetone Beetroot Red), microbial pigments for stability.",
